var BOOK5_ROADMAP = {sections:[{id:'ch0s1',num:'0.1',title:'The Posture: Mechanism Before Vocabulary',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Psychology and sociology are the subjects pre-meds most often try to study by making flashcards of terms, and they are the subjects where that strategy fails most quietly. The vocabulary is easy to learn and the understanding is easy to fake, until the exam shows otherwise. The MCAT does not ask you to define \'negative reinforcement\' or \'fundamental attribution error.\' It gives you a research scenario, describes a behavioral result, and asks which concept best explains it. The only way to answer that reliably is to understand the mechanism well enough to recognize it in any setting.'},{t:'p',x:'This book teaches mechanisms first: why operant conditioning produces the behaviors it does, not just what its terms mean; why the fundamental attribution error is so robust, not just what it is called; why social stratification predicts health outcomes, not just that it does. Vocabulary is the label on the jar. Mechanism is what is inside.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MEMORIZING TERMS vs UNDERSTANDING MECHANISMS',x:'MEMORIZING stores a term and a one-line definition. It appears to work until a question places the concept in an unfamiliar research context, at which point the definition is useless. UNDERSTANDING stores the mechanism, the process by which the phenomenon arises, which lets you recognize it in any context and distinguish it from superficially similar concepts. The MCAT tests psychology and sociology in unfamiliar research scenarios precisely to reward the second approach. Learn how the mechanism works, then attach the vocabulary to it.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: WHY A FUTURE PHYSICIAN STUDIES BEHAVIORAL SCIENCE',x:'Behavioral and social sciences are not peripheral to clinical medicine; they are central to it. Health behaviors, the choices patients make about diet, smoking, exercise, and screening, account for a larger share of preventable morbidity and mortality than any single disease mechanism. The therapeutic alliance, how well a patient trusts and communicates with their physician, is one of the strongest predictors of treatment adherence and outcome. Attribution theory explains how patients assign meaning to illness, which determines whether they seek care at all. Social support networks are protective against depression, cardiovascular disease, and all-cause mortality. The social determinants of health explain why poverty, education, race, and geography predict health outcomes more powerfully than most clinical variables. Every chapter of this book has a direct pathway to clinical practice.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'STUDY TIP: THREE HABITS THAT PAY OFF IN PSYCH/SOC',x:'First, learn vocabulary paired with mechanism: do not store the name of a theorist without also storing what their theory claims and why it matters. Second, know your named theorists: the MCAT frequently identifies a concept by its originator, so Piaget\'s stages, Erikson\'s crises, Kohlberg\'s moral reasoning, Bandura\'s social learning, and Freud\'s psychodynamic model must each be tied to a specific mechanism or prediction. Third, anchor everything to the biopsychosocial model: biological, psychological, and social factors interact to produce health and illness, and the MCAT uses this framework to connect concepts across chapters.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher describes a study in which a rat presses a lever more frequently after receiving food only when the lever-press rate exceeds a threshold. An MCAT question asks which type of reinforcement schedule this represents. A student who only memorized the definition of \'variable ratio schedule\' cannot answer. What would have helped?',choices:['A) Memorizing a longer list that includes the threshold criterion as part of the definition','B) Understanding the mechanism: ratio schedules tie reinforcement to the number of responses, and a fixed ratio requires a set number while a variable ratio uses an average, producing high steady response rates because the next reinforcement is always close','C) Reviewing the schedule names one more time before the exam','D) Skipping reinforcement schedules and focusing on classical conditioning instead'],answer:1,why:'Mechanism-based understanding lets you reason about novel scenarios. Knowing that ratio schedules reinforce based on number of responses, and that variable ratios use an average count, allows you to identify the schedule from its behavioral description rather than from a memorized label. Definition alone cannot handle an unfamiliar behavioral result.'}]},{id:'ch0s2',num:'0.2',title:'The Four Moves and How This Book Is Built',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Every chapter in Book 5 trains the same four cognitive moves. First, think mechanism: before learning a term, ask what psychological or social process underlies it and why it produces the outcomes it does. Second, trust the discriminator: for any two concepts that look alike, negative reinforcement versus punishment, encoding failure versus retrieval failure, prejudice versus discrimination, in-group versus out-group bias, find the single distinction that separates them cleanly. Third, pivot fast: identify the mechanism and commit to your answer. Fourth, revisit in 48 hours: re-explain each mechanism from its underlying logic two days later, the window where memory consolidation is most improvable.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'THE FOUR MOVES',x:'Think mechanism: ask why a phenomenon occurs before learning its name. Trust the discriminator: find the one distinction separating confusable concepts. Pivot fast: identify the mechanism, select the answer, and commit. Revisit in 48 hours: re-explain each mechanism from its logic two days after learning it.'},{t:'p',x:'The same colored boxes appear in every chapter of the series. The gold DISCRIMINATOR box isolates the single distinction you are most likely to get wrong; psychology and sociology are full of them: classical versus operant conditioning, encoding versus retrieval, prejudice versus discrimination, role versus status, class versus caste. The blue CLINICAL BRIDGE box shows where the concept becomes patient care. The purple WHY box explains where a finding comes from. The HIGH-YIELD box compresses the must-know facts of a section into a short testable list. Read the boxes actively: predict each discriminator before reading it, and reconstruct the mechanism behind each clinical bridge.'},{t:'p',x:'Read the chapters in order. The book is built so that each layer assumes the ones before it: the neurobiology of Chapter 1 grounds the sensation and perception of Chapter 2, the learning mechanisms of Chapter 3 underlie the memory systems of Chapter 4, the social cognition of Chapter 10 requires the understanding of attitudes and self developed in earlier chapters, and the structural sociology of Chapters 12 and 13 assumes the social psychology of Chapters 10 and 11. On a first pass, read for mechanism and resist the urge to make vocabulary lists. On a second pass, drill the high-yield anchors and question banks, and use the cheat sheets for rapid review.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY ORDER MATTERS IN THIS BOOK',x:'Psychology and sociology are more cumulative than they appear. The conditioning of Chapter 3 reappears in the motivation theory of Chapter 6 and the behavioral therapies of Chapter 9. The developmental stages of Chapter 7 reappear as the background for personality in Chapter 8 and for socialization in Chapter 12. The social cognition of Chapter 10 is the foundation of the group processes of Chapter 11 and the structural inequalities of Chapter 13. Reading in order builds a connected understanding in which each idea is grounded in what came before; reading out of order produces a flat list of terms with no web of connection to hold them.'},{t:'list',x:['Ch 1: Biological Foundations of Behavior - neurons, brain regions, hormones, and the neural substrate all of psychology is built on','Ch 2: Sensation and Perception - transduction, thresholds, signal detection, perceptual organization, and sensory adaptation','Ch 3: Learning, Conditioning, and Memory - classical and operant conditioning, observational learning, memory encoding, storage, and retrieval','Ch 4: Cognition, Language, and Intelligence - problem solving, heuristics, language acquisition, and IQ measurement','Ch 5: States of Consciousness - sleep stages, circadian rhythms, hypnosis, meditation, and psychoactive drugs','Ch 6: Motivation, Emotion, and Stress - drive and incentive theories, emotional appraisal, the stress response, and the biopsychosocial model of health','Ch 7: Development Across the Lifespan - Piaget, Erikson, Kohlberg, Vygotsky, and the major milestones from infancy through late adulthood','Ch 8: Personality - psychodynamic, humanistic, trait, and social-cognitive approaches; assessment methods','Ch 9: Psychological Disorders and Treatment - DSM categories, psychological and biological therapies, their mechanisms','Ch 10: Social Cognition - attribution, attitudes, cognitive dissonance, stereotypes, prejudice, discrimination, and self-concept','Ch 11: Social Influence and Group Processes - conformity, obedience, group dynamics, prosocial behavior, and aggression','Ch 12: Social Structure, Culture, and Identity - social institutions, socialization, culture, norms, and identity formation','Ch 13: Inequality, Demographics, and Health - stratification, social determinants of health, race, gender, aging, and epidemiology']}],quickcheck:[]}]};

